    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"PowerShell check WHEA-Logger event viewer logs temperature sensors hardware status\", \"numResults\": 5}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_f83f1ca747fc471ca823b0adef989177\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://forum.level1techs.com/t/whea-logger-18-and-kernel-event-id-41/219554\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA-Logger 18 and Kernel Event ID 41 - CPU - Level1Techs Forums\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-12\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"[Return to Level1Techs.com](http://level1techs.com)\\n\\nLevel1Techs Forums\\n\\n# WHEA-Logger 18 and Kernel Event ID 41\\n\\nHardware Hub CPU\\n\\n[ryzen](https://forum.level1techs.com/tag/ryzen)\\n\\n[SiK](https://forum.level1techs.com/u/SiK) November 4, 2024, 7:42pm 1\\n\\nBefore I formatted my PC, everything was working perfectly. I decided to do a fresh install to create clean drives and start new. However, now I’m experiencing WHEA-Logger 18 and Kernel Event ID 41 crashes. Before the format, my PC worked smoothly without any crashes.\\n\\n[Screenshot 2024-11-04 203938 Screenshot 2024-11-04 203938 2560×1392 119 KB](https://level1techs.us-east-1.linodeobjects.com/original/4X/e/c/5/ec58ac2d2cb015ba3d217553c02df9a9631cab64.png \\\"Screenshot 2024-11-04 203938\\\")\\n\\n[Screenshot 2024-11-04 204012 Screenshot 2024-11-04 204012 2560×1392 122 KB](https://level1techs.us-east-1.linodeobjects.com/original/4X/e/0/c/e0c44fce9461163997c8f7c46c893365e42c1b08.png \\\"Screenshot 2024-11-04 204012\\\")\\n\\nScreenshot 2024-11-04 204108\\nScreenshot 2024-11-04 204106  \\nScreenshot 2024-11-04 204059  \\nScreenshot 2024-11-04 204057  \\nScreenshot 2024-11-04 204054\\n\\n[SiK](https://forum.level1techs.com/u/SiK) November 4, 2024, 10:01pm 2\\n\\nI reset the BIOS to default settings, but the same issue persisted. I then changed my CPU to a 5800X, yet the problem remains. I also tried restoring the BIOS to its default settings again and updated to the latest BIOS version, using the normal RAM profile.\\n\\n[MetalizeYourBrain](https://forum.level1techs.com/u/MetalizeYourBrain) November 6, 2024, 1:26pm 3\\n\\nIs it always the same ACPI ID in the crashes? Are there any recurrent conditions in which the crash happens? Are you using different peripherals or connections like wifi or bluetooth?\\n\\n[SiK](https://forum.level1techs.com/u/SiK) November 6, 2024, 2:42pm 4\\n\\n“OK, so now I ran some tests. I am facing an issue with RAM in a Windows environment, where the computer frequently crashes with WHEA-Logger 18 and Kernel Event ID 41 errors.\\nI have performed several tests, including swapping the processor, but the issue seems to be related to the RAM. The computer crashes when all four memory modules are active, but the error does not occur when only two modules are used. I have also tested with different RAM modules, and the computer works normally, even when all four modules are in use.”\\n\\n[MetalizeYourBrain](https://forum.level1techs.com/u/MetalizeYourBrain) November 6, 2024, 2:56pm 5\\n\\nUsually different software mitigations can put under stress the system in ways it wasn’t before and make it unstable.  \\nWhat you could try to do to make it stable with four sticks of RAM is taking note of the APIC ID of the core that’s giving you issues and giving it a bit more voltage using the PBO positive offset in the BIOS. This will increase the power consumption and heat output of the processor so if you don’t have enough cooling you should not do this.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/229e1635-6cdc-4980-ac6e-e4257c3ba316/event-id-17-whea-logger?forum=windows-all\",\n      \"title\": \"Event ID 17 WHEA Logger - Microsoft Q&A\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"I've searched it in Device Manager, and it appears to be an \\\"Intel PEG10 - 460D\\\", something for drivers i think.  \\nI've tried updating my BIOS, updating drivers, however nothing worked, and the error still persists. Any fix or help is very appreciated.\\n\\nLocked Question. This question was migrated from the Microsoft Support Community. You can vote on whether it's helpful, but you can't add comments or replies or follow the question.\\n\\n0 comments No comments Report a concern\\n\\nI have the same question I have the same question 1 {count} vote\\n\\n## 1 answer\\n\\n1. Anonymous\\n   \\n   2024-11-09T06:32:38+00:00\\n   \\n   Hi, FrancescoCN\\n   \\n   Welcome to the Microsoft Community.\\n   \\n   Thank you for your feedback. From the Event Viewer screenshot you posted, it appears that this is a hardware error logged by the Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA) logger, specifically related to the PCI Express root port. Here are some troubleshooting options:\\n   \\n    1.\\nSometimes, BIOS and chipset driver updates can fix hardware compatibility issues. Visit your motherboard manufacturer's official website to check if new BIOS and chipset drivers are available for download.\\n    2. Check PCIe slots and graphics cards: Make sure your graphics card and other PCIe devices are properly inserted into the slots without loose or bad contacts. Replace the PCIe slot: If possible, insert your graphics card or other PCIe devices into another slot and see if the problem persists.\\n    3. Check the power supply: Inadequate power supply may cause hardware anomalies. Make sure your power supply is strong enough to provide a stable supply to all hardware devices. If you are not sure, try using a higher power supply.\\n    4. System Stability Test\\n   \\n   Run hardware diagnostic tools: Run some hardware diagnostic tools (such as MemTest86, Prime95, or FurMark) to test the stability of your memory, CPU, and graphics card.\\nCheck system temperature: Use a tool such as HWMonitor or MSI Afterburner to monitor your system temperature and make sure there are no overheating issues.\\n   \\n    1. Reduce system load: If your system has been running high load tasks for a long time, try reducing the system load to see if the problem goes away. Try lowering your game's graphics settings to see if the problem persists.\\n    2. To troubleshoot system problems, you can try reinstalling windows using USB installation media. before doing this, please backup your important data.\\n   \\n   [How to: Perform a Custom Installation of Windows 11 and Windows 10 - Microsoft Community](https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/all/how-to-perform-a-custom-installation-of-windows-11/38adfa8c-32f8-4354-8c53-13b5f2cf7e44 \\\"answers.microsoft.com\\\")\\n   \\n   If the above methods don't work, we suggest you contact a professional computer repairer or after-sales service provider to get help.\\n   \\n   I look forward to your feedback.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/whea/querying-the-system-event-log-for-hardware-error-events\",\n      \"title\": \"Querying the System Event Log for Hardware Error Events - Windows drivers | Microsoft Learn\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-12-17\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Skip to main content Skip to Ask Learn chat experience\\n\\nTable of contents Exit editor mode\\n\\nFocus mode Table of contents Read in English Add [Edit](https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/windows-driver-docs/blob/staging/windows-driver-docs-pr/whea/querying-the-system-event-log-for-hardware-error-events.md)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n#### Share via\\n\\nFacebook x.com LinkedIn Email\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nPrint\\n\\n# Querying the System Event Log for Hardware Error Events\\n\\n* 2024-12-17\\n\\n## In this article\\n\\nThe name of the provider that logs the hardware error events is **Microsoft-Windows-WHEA-Logger** .\\n\\nThis provider is designed for users in desktop scenarios. It provides a human readable message with the main details of the event so a user can get a basic idea of what occurred.\\n\\nThe following code example shows how to query the system event log to retrieve any hardware error events that were previously logged by the Windows Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA).\\n\\n```\\n// Function to query the event log for hardware error events\\nVOID QueryHwErrorEvents(VOID) {\\n\\n  EVT_HANDLE QueryHandle;\\n  EVT_HANDLE EventHandle;\\n  ULONG Returned;\\n\\n  // Obtain a query handle to the system event log\\n  QueryHandle =\\n    EvtQuery(\\n      NULL, \\n      L\\\"System\\\", \\n      L\\\"*[System/Provider[@Name=\\\\\\\"Microsoft-Windows-WHEA-Logger\\\\\\\"]]\\\",\\n      EvtQueryChannelPath | EvtQueryForwardDirection\\n      );\\n\\n  // Check result\\n  if (QueryHandle != NULL) {\\n\\n    // Get the next hardware error event\\n    while (EvtNext(\\n             QueryHandle,\\n             1,\\n             &EventHandle,\\n             -1,\\n             0,\\n             &Returned\\n             )) {\\n\\n      // Process the hardware error event\\n      ProcessHwErrorEvent(EventHandle);\\n\\n      // Close the event handle\\n      EvtClose(EventHandle);\\n    }\\n\\n    // Close the query handle\\n    EvtClose(QueryHandle);\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNote\\nAll of the **Evt\\\\_Xxx\\\\_** functions and the EVT\\\\_ _XXX_ data types that were used in the previous examples are documented in the Windows Event Log section in the Microsoft Windows SDK documentation.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Feedback\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\nYes No\\n\\n### In this article\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\nYes No\\n\\nen-us\\n\\nTheme\\n\\n* Light\\n* Dark\\n* High contrast\\n\\n* [AI Disclaimer](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/principles-for-ai-generated-content)\\n* [Previous Versions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/)\\n* [Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-learn-blog/bg-p/MicrosoftLearnBlog)\\n* [Contribute](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/contribute)\\n* [Privacy](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=521839)\\n* [Terms of Use](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/legal/termsofuse)\\n* [Trademarks](https://www.microsoft.com/legal/intellectualproperty/Trademarks/)\\n* © Microsoft 2025\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.anavem.com/en/windows-events/windows-event-id-17-whea-logger-hardware-error\",\n      \"title\": \"Event ID 17: WHEA-Logger Hardware Error Correction Guide\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-03-18\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"text=Windows%20Event%20ID%2017%20%E2%80%93%20WHEA-Logger%3A%20Hardware%20Error%20Architecture%20Corrected%20Error%20%23eventid17%20%23whealogger%20%23hardwaremonitoring&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.anavem.com%2Fen%2Fwindows-events%2Fwindows-event-id-17-whea-logger-hardware-error) [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.anavem.com%2Fen%2Fwindows-events%2Fwindows-event-id-17-whea-logger-hardware-error) [Reddit](https://reddit.com/submit?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.anavem.com%2Fen%2Fwindows-events%2Fwindows-event-id-17-whea-logger-hardware-error&title=Windows%20Event%20ID%2017%20%E2%80%93%20WHEA-Logger%3A%20Hardware%20Error%20Architecture%20Corrected%20Error) Email Copy link\\n\\nEvent ID 17 Information WHEA-Logger Windows\\n\\n# Windows Event ID 17 – WHEA-Logger: Hardware Error Architecture Corrected Error\\n\\nEvent ID 17 from WHEA-Logger indicates Windows Hardware Error Architecture detected and corrected a hardware error.\\nThis informational event helps track system stability and potential hardware degradation.\\n\\nEmanuel De Almeida Emanuel De Almeida\\n\\n18 March 2026 9min read —\\n\\nSave\\n\\nServer monitoring room displaying Windows Event Viewer with WHEA-Logger hardware error events\\n\\n Reference Windows Events Windows Event ID 17 – WHEA-Logger: Hardware Error Architecture Corrected Error\\n\\nEvent ID 17 WHEA-Logger 5methods 9 min\\n\\nEvent Reference\\n\\n## What This Event Means\\n\\nWindows Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA) represents Microsoft's comprehensive approach to hardware error detection and reporting, significantly enhanced in Windows 11 2024 updates and Windows Server 2025. Event ID 17 specifically indicates that WHEA successfully intercepted and corrected a hardware error before it could impact system operation or data integrity.\\nThe architecture works by collecting error information from various hardware sources including processors with Machine Check Architecture (MCA), memory controllers with Error Correction Code (ECC) capabilities, and PCIe devices supporting Advanced Error Reporting (AER). When correctable errors occur, WHEA creates standardized error records containing detailed diagnostic information about the error source, type, and correction method applied.\\n\\nThese corrected errors typically include single-bit memory errors automatically fixed by ECC, CPU cache line corrections handled by internal error correction circuits, and PCIe transaction retries managed by link-layer protocols. While individually harmless, patterns in these events can reveal emerging hardware issues such as memory module degradation, thermal stress on processors, or signal integrity problems in high-speed interconnects.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.elevenforum.com/t/warning-whea-logger-daily-errors.35407\",\n      \"title\": \"Warning. WHEA-Logger - Daily Errors | Windows 11 Forum\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-04-22\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"### [Intel® Chipset Software and Drivers](https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000005533/software/chipset-software.html)\\n\\nWhere to find Intel® chipset software and drivers support for Intel® products.\\n\\nwww.intel.com www.intel.com\\n\\n### My Computer\\n\\n### At a glance\\n\\nWindows 11 AMD Ryzen 7 5700G Micron Technology DDR4-3200 16GB NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060\\n\\nOS\\n    Windows 11\\n\\nComputer type\\n    PC/Desktop\\n\\nManufacturer/Model\\n    HP Pavilion\\n\\nCPU\\n    AMD Ryzen 7 5700G\\n\\nMotherboard\\n    Erica6\\n\\nMemory\\n    Micron Technology DDR4-3200 16GB\\n\\nGraphics Card(s)\\n    NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060\\n\\nSound Card\\n    Realtek ALC671\\n\\nMonitor(s) Displays\\n    Samsung SyncMaster U28E590\\n\\nScreen Resolution\\n    3840 x 2160\\n\\nHard Drives\\n    SAMSUNG MZVLQ1T0HALB-000H1\\n\\n* Like\\n\\nReactions: otronics\\n\\nO\\n\\n#### otronics\\n\\n##### New member\\n\\nThread Starter\\n\\nLocal time\\n    6:50 AM\\n\\nPosts\\n    4\\n\\nOS\\n    Windows 11\\n\\n* Apr 23, 2025\\n\\n* \\n* \\n* \\\\#5\\n\\nSorted. Installing the latest ethernet driver fixed it.\\n### My Computer\\n\\n### At a glance\\n\\nWindows 11\\n\\nOS\\n    Windows 11\\n\\nComputer type\\n    Laptop\\n\\n* Like\\n\\nReactions: werty and Aramil\\n\\nYou must log in or register to reply here.\\n\\nShare:\\n\\nFacebook LinkedIn Reddit WhatsApp Email Share Link\\n\\n### Latest Support Threads\\n\\n* Awesomehorse\\n  \\n  A weird blank empty white box appears briefly after boot-up\\n  \\n    + Started by Awesomehorse\\n    + Yesterday at 10:48 PM\\n    + Replies: 1\\n  \\n  General Support\\n* T\\n  \\n  Manually force a program to open in the background?\\n  \\n    + Started by Titanonectes\\n    + Yesterday at 9:22 PM\\n    + Replies: 3\\n  \\n  Apps and Software\\n* I\\n  \\n  Dell laptop doesn't turn on and roomate's PC is frozen\\n  \\n    + Started by IvanDrago\\n    + Yesterday at 7:06 PM\\n    + Replies: 2\\n  \\n  General Support\\n* J\\n  \\n  Windows 11 Settings App Crashes when selecting Location, Camera, or Microphone\\n  \\n    + Started by Jim Rockford\\n    + Yesterday at 6:55 PM\\n    + Replies: 5\\n  \\n  General Support\\n* Baeolophus\\nHow to enable MFA on local account without Microsoft account\\n  \\n    + Started by Baeolophus\\n    + Yesterday at 3:52 PM\\n    + Replies: 2\\n  \\n  AntiVirus, Firewalls and System Security\\n\\n### Latest Tutorials\\n\\n* \\n  \\n  System Enable or Disable Notifications for Reminders and VoIP calls on Lock Screen in Windows 11\\n  \\n    + Started by Brink\\n    + Yesterday at 12:51 PM\\n    + Replies: 0\\n  \\n  Tutorials\\n* \\n  \\n  Browsers and Mail Enable or Disable Sign-in to Microsoft Edge using non-Microsoft accounts in Windows 11\\n  \\n    + Started by Brink\\n    + Monday at 10:45 AM\\n    + Replies: 0\\n  \\n  Tutorials\\n* \\n  \\n  Personalization Change Taskbar Size in Windows 11\\n  \\n    + Started by Brink\\n    + Jun 26, 2026\\n    + Replies: 1\\n  \\n  Tutorials\\n* \\n  \\n  Backup and Restore Delete Restore Points for System Restore and Point-in-time Restore in Windows 11\\n  \\n    + Started by Brink\\n    + Jun 26, 2026\\n    + Replies: 2\\n  \\n  Tutorials\\n*\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/whea/whea-hardware-error-events\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Hardware Error Events - Windows drivers | Microsoft Learn\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Skip to main content Skip to Ask Learn chat experience\\n\\nTable of contents Exit editor mode\\n\\nFocus mode Table of contents Read in English Add [Edit](https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/windows-driver-docs/blob/staging/windows-driver-docs-pr/whea/whea-hardware-error-events.md)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n#### Share via\\n\\nFacebook x.com LinkedIn Email\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nPrint\\n\\n# WHEA Hardware Error Events\\n\\n* 2024-12-16\\n\\n## In this article\\n\\nThe Windows Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA) raises an Event Tracing for Windows (ETW) event whenever a hardware error occurs. These hardware error events are recorded in the system event log. For descriptions of the various hardware error events that can be raised by WHEA, see Hardware Error Events .\\n\\nAn application can retrieve hardware error events from the system event log by querying for any events that were logged by WHEA. For examples of how to retrieve WHEA hardware error events from the system event log, see Querying the System Event Log for Hardware Error Events .\\nAn application can also register to be notified whenever new hardware error events are raised by WHEA. For examples of how to register for the notification of new hardware error events, see Registering for Notification of Hardware Error Events .\\n\\nRegardless of whether a particular hardware error event was obtained by querying the system event log or by receiving an event notification, the process of retrieving the hardware error data from the event is the same.\\n\\nEach hardware error event contains an error record that describes the error condition that occurred. The error record can be retrieved from each event for further analysis.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Feedback\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\nYes No\\n\\n### In this article\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\nYes No\\n\\nen-us\\n\\nTheme\\n\\n* Light\\n* Dark\\n* High contrast\\n\\n* [AI Disclaimer](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/principles-for-ai-generated-content)\\n* [Previous Versions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/)\\n* [Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.\\ncom/t5/microsoft-learn-blog/bg-p/MicrosoftLearnBlog)\\n* [Contribute](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/contribute)\\n* [Privacy](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=521839)\\n* [Terms of Use](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/legal/termsofuse)\\n* [Trademarks](https://www.microsoft.com/legal/intellectualproperty/Trademarks/)\\n* © Microsoft 2025\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.techpowerup.com/forums/threads/whea-logger-fatal-hardware-error.279436\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Logger Fatal Hardware error | TechPowerUp Forums\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"# Automated bot check in progress\\n\\nThis should only take a few seconds. If you have issues, please do contact us, we want to learn about any problems.\\n\\nNeed help? Contact Us . Please mention your IP: 23.236.55.230\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/1664747/whea-logger-says-fatal-hardware-error-occurred?page=1\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA-Logger says Fatal Hardware Error Occurred - Microsoft Q&A\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"This bro